stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: RTF document containing a Zeus/ZBot binary
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description: On June 26, 2013, a malicious RTF document was submitted for analysis. The document contained shellcode that decrypts, drops, and executes a Zeus/ZBot binary. The malware was found to exploit the vulnerability described in CVE-012-0158. Also, twenty (20) C2 IP addresses were identified during analysis.

stix:Indicator.indicator:Description:
Antivirus Identifier: Kaspersky: Exploit.Win32.CVE-2012-0158.j McAfee: Exploit-CVE2012-0158!rtf Microsoft: Exploit:Win32/CVE-2012-0158.CJ Symantec: Trojan.Mdropper TrendMicro TROJ_ARTIEF.HAL
This document is a RTF file with its extension changed to ".doc" to ensure Microsoft Word will be the application opening it. It contains shellcode that decrypts, drops, and executes a Zeus/ZBot binary. When launched by the user, the shellcode first decodes the encrypted binary. The decoding routine consists of a single XOR key, which can be found at offset 17A0Bh in the document. xor byte ptr [ebx], 3Fh ; '?' ; decryption key inc ebx dec eax cmp eax, 0 jnz short loc_23F ; decryption loop
Once decoded, the shellcode saves the file to the location, "%TEMP%\paw.exe". The dropped file will then be executed with WinExec, and the original shellcode will terminate by calling ExitProcess
APIs of interested resolved by the shellcode: mov dword ptr [edi], 0BBAFDF85h ; GetProcAddress mov dword ptr [edi+4], 0AC0A138Eh ; GetFileSize mov dword ptr [edi+8], 9424D45Ah ; GlobalAlloc mov dword ptr [edi+0Ch], 0DBACBE43h ; SetFilePointer mov dword ptr [edi+10h], 130F36B2h ; ReadFile mov dword ptr [edi+14h], 94E43293h ; CreateFileA mov dword ptr [edi+18h], 837DE239h ; GetTempPathA mov dword ptr [edi+1Ch], 741F8DC4h ; WriteFile mov dword ptr [edi+20h], 0FF0D6657h ; CloseHandle mov dword ptr [edi+24h], 1A22F51h ; WinExec mov dword ptr [edi+28h], 0B4FFAFEDh ; GetModuleFileNameA mov dword ptr [edi+2Ch], 4FD18963h ; ExitProcess

Antivirus Identifier: Kaspersky: Trojan-Spy.Win32.Zbot.lnas McAfee: Artemis!102AC9221CA0 Microsoft: PWS:Win32/Zbot.gen!AM
This dropped executable is a P2P Zeus bot. It has been packed with an unidentified packer to hinder static analysis.
On execution, the malware generates an infection_id by using the computer name, windows version, volume ID. The infection_id and the drop location is written to the executable file which is then copied to the location, "%APPDATA%\[random_folder]\[random_name.exe]". The executable will then create a new process with the dropped file. Finally, the malware deletes itself with the embedded batch command: :d del "%s" if exist "%s" goto d

This is the P2P Zeus copy dropped by "paw.exe" (MD5: 102ac9221ca096ce2c960bc3e2efc2c2). This file creates the following registry value for persistence: \\HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run\[Generated_SID]
When executed, this binary first compares the 'infection_id' string to the values on the running system. If the values match, the bot will then check that this binary was executed from its expected location (%APPDAT%\[random_folder]\[random_name.exe]). If everything passes, this bot injects into winlogon.exe. Next, it attempts to connect and update the P2P Zeus trackers by sending encrypted data via a UDP transmission to 20 different IP addresses and over high numbered ports.
It then tests for internet connectivity by connecting to www.google.com and www.bing.com, followed by using a domain generation algorithm to request a valid C2 server.
